06015nam a22009375i 9789048544592DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20202020ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485445927 a10.1515/97890485445922doi  a(DE-B1597)576358  a(OCoLC)1226584394  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 4aNA2795.5b.E35 2021 7aARC0050402bisacsh04a72122300aEarly Modern Spaces in Motion :bDesign, Experience and Rhetoric /ced. by Kimberley Skelton. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (274 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aVisual and Material Culture, 1300 –1700 ;v2600tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction: Bodies and Buildings in Motion -- t1. Navigating the Palace Underworld : Recreational Space, Pleasure, and Release at the Castello del Buonconsiglio, Trent -- t2. Passages to Fantasy : The Performance of Motion in Cellini’s Fontainebleau Portal and the Galerie François I -- t3. The Catholic Country House in Early Modern England : Motion, Piety and Hospitality, c. 1580–1640 -- t4. Sensory Vibrations and Social Reform at San Michele a Ripa in Rome -- t5. The Rise of the Staircase : Motion in Eighteenth-Century Dutch Domestic Architecture -- t6. Movement through Ruins: Re-experiencing Ancient Baalbek with Jean de la Roque -- t7. A Paper Tour of the Metropolis : The Architecture of Early Modern London in the Royal Magazine -- t8. Libraries in Motion: Forms of Movement in the Early Modern Library (1450-1770) -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aStretching back to antiquity, motion had been a key means of designing and describing the physical environment. But during the sixteenth through eighteenth centuries, individuals across Europe increasingly designed, experienced, and described a new world of motion: one characterized by continuous, rather than segmented, movement. New spaces that included vistas along house interiors and uninterrupted library reading rooms offered open expanses for shaping sequences of social behaviour, scientists observed how the Earth rotated around the sun, and philosophers attributed emotions to neural vibrations in the human brain. Early Modern Spaces in Motion examines this increased emphasis on motion with eight essays encompassing a geographical span of Portugal to German-speaking lands and a disciplinary range from architectural history to English. It consequently merges longstanding strands of analysis considering people in motion and buildings in motion to explore the cultural historical attitudes underpinning the varied impacts of motion in early modern Europe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aArchitecture and societyzEuropexHistoryy16th century. 0aArchitecture and societyzEuropexHistoryy17th century. 0aArchitecture and societyzEuropexHistoryy18th century. 0aArchitecturezEuropexHistoryy16th century. 0aArchitecturezEuropexHistoryy17th century. 0aArchitecturezEuropexHistoryy18th century. 0aMotion in architecture. 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aEarly Modern Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 7aARCHITECTURE / History / Renaissance.2bisacsh  a1. architecture 2. early modern 3. Europe 4. motion.1 aAnderson, Jocelyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBensoussan, Nicole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampbell, James W. P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJakovac, Gašper, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchmidt, Freek, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel